1. pom.xml

<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 
                             http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <groupId>com.yourorg</groupId>
  <artifactId>indicator-daily-sync-test</artifactId>
  <version>1.0.0</version>

  <properties>
    <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
    <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    <karate.version>1.4.1</karate.version>
  </properties>

  <dependencies>
    <!-- Dependency on your Karate tests snapshot -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.yourorg</groupId>
      <artifactId>karate-tests</artifactId>
      <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    </dependency>

    <!-- Karate JUnit 5 for the test runner -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.intuit.karate</groupId>
      <artifactId>karate-junit5</artifactId>
      <version>${karate.version}</version>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <repositories>
    <repository>
      <id>artifactory-snapshots</id>
      <url>https://yourcompany.jfrog.io/artifactory/libs-snapshot</url>
    </repository>
  </repositories>

  <build>
    <plugins>
      <plugin>
        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
        <artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId>
        <version>3.2.5</version>
        <configuration>
          <systemPropertyVariables>
            <!-- Pass environment variables and Karate options from command line -->
            <karate.env>${karate.env}</karate.env>
            <user.name>${user.name}</user.name>
            <user.pass>${user.pass}</user.pass>
            <karate.options>${karate.options}</karate.options>
          </systemPropertyVariables>
        </configuration>
      </plugin>
    </plugins>
  </build>

</project>


â¸»

2. TestRunner.java

Create this file under src/test/java/com/yourorg/runner/TestRunner.java:

package com.yourorg.runner;

import com.intuit.karate.junit5.Karate;

public class TestRunner {

    @Karate.Test
    Karate testAll() {
        // Run all feature files from the classpath (your snapshot jar)
        return Karate.run().relativeTo(getClass());
    }

}


â¸»

3. How to Run Tests

You must pass environment and sensitive variables at runtime (e.g., from Bamboo or CLI):

mvn clean test \
  -Dkarate.env=qa \
  -Duser.name=someuser \
  -Duser.pass=somepassword \
  -Dkarate.options="--tags @daily"

	â€¢	karate.env: sets the environment, read inside karate-config.js
	â€¢	user.name, user.pass: read securely inside your karate-config.js via karate.properties[]
	â€¢	karate.options: pass Karate CLI options like --tags

â¸»

4. Bamboo Setup (Example)
	â€¢	Add Bamboo Plan Variables or Secure Variables for user.name, user.pass
	â€¢	Use a Maven task with goal:

clean test \
  -Dkarate.env=${bamboo_env} \
  -Duser.name=${bamboo_USER} \
  -Duser.pass=${bamboo_PASS} \
  -Dkarate.options="--tags @daily"

Replace ${bamboo_env}, ${bamboo_USER}, ${bamboo_PASS} with Bamboo variable references.

â¸»

5. Notes
	â€¢	This runner does not contain feature files or credentials â€” it relies on the Karate snapshot JAR dependency.
	â€¢	Your Karate snapshot JAR (artifact com.yourorg:karate-tests:1.0.0-SNAPSHOT) must be deployed to your Artifactory snapshot repo before running this.
	â€¢	karate-config.js inside that snapshot JAR should read sensitive info like this:

function fn() {
  var config = {};
  config.env = karate.env; // from -Dkarate.env
  config.username = karate.properties['user.name'];
  config.password = karate.properties['user.pass'];
  return config;
}


